title: Universal Joint for 1/4-20 threaded rods and bolts

description.text:
This is a universal joint made to lock onto 1/4-20 threaded rods and bolts. I made it for a robot arm I'm designing, the rest of which will be shared when it's finalized. I've reprinted it a few times to make sure it snaps together easily but still stays together in use. To see a description of the project it is for and a video of it in action check out the Milwaukee Makerspace blog. There is also a link if you want to vote for my project on element14:
http://milwaukeemakerspace.org/2014/01/a-robot-barista-a-new-open-source-robot-arm-design-and-a-call-for-votes/ I printed it at 100% fill from PLA with 2 shells, on a Makerbot Replicator 2 with the spring lever upgrade on a bed covered in scotch blue painters tape.

I printed these from PLA, 100% fill, 0.30 layer thickness, 2 shells. Required supplies:
The two 1/4-20 threaded rods or nuts you want to join
4 nuts, you can jam them, use lock nuts, or even locktite them Print:
2 of "universal_joint_end.stl"
1 of "universal_joint_toggle.stl" Assemble:
1.Drop one nut into the socket between the prongs of each end. This is a hex to capture the nut, over-sized to account for wall expansion during printing (0.45" span) so the nut should press fit in nicely.
  • Put a nut onto each of the two threaded ends you want to join and run it down to make room for the rod end.
    • 3.Screw the ends on and jam the nuts up against the ends, try to get the rod end even with the nut on the inside. If you are using locktite or another nut adhesive, add it now. 4.Rock the toggle in to place, there are slopes in the ends of the tabs to make this easier to do from straight on. Then snap the other end onto it.

title: 2007 Specialized FSR Elite Rear Shock Guard

description.text:
This is a guard to help minimize the amount of dirt and dust directed onto the rear shock by the rear wheel for a 2007 Specialized FSR Elite. As I have just replaced the rear shock and noticed some wear possibly due to dust and grim sticking to the shock, I figured this would hopefully help prevent unnecessary damage while giving me a fun project. Inspiration was taken from the front fork guards I had seen on motocross bikes.

Installation does require unbolting the shock from the linkage. Other than that, it simply slips into place and is held by the linkage.

This is a very specific fit as it relies on the shape of the shock and the spacers that mount it in the linkage of the rear suspension. If anyone else has this decade old bike around that was only made with this particular rear linkage configuration for 2-3 years, it will probably help them out. Otherwise, I don't think it will fit directly on anything else.

Update: Finally made it out for a ride and it worked very well. Picture included.

author: Carlikus

description.text: for 8.5mm motors

I designed this using the Open Rocketry which is a model rocketry simulator. The simulations I ran on it indicates it will reach a height of almost 2,500 feet. The rocket has a stability of 1.00 caliber with both stages and a 1.22 caliber for just the upper stage. So far I've done 3 tests launches with this rocket and the model rocket proved to be very stable on all of the tests even in some decent wind. We lost sight of the rocket 2 out of the 3 times. The time that we did see where it landed, we were unable to recover it. If you do plan on actually launching this rocket you need a clear day and a ton of space. I named my rocket the Flaming Eagle and I added a really cool flame design to the paint.

Main Rocket

For the body tube, you need a 33mm diameter cardboard tube. If you're buying your buying the body tube from Estates, it will be a BT-55 sized tube. The length of the body tube is 10cm. The parachute is just a cheap 12in Estates parachute that will have to be attached to a shock cord (any rubber band will work as long as it's strong enough not to break). I also added a ribbon on the shock cord the holds the parachute to assist in the parachute deployment. You'll also notice that in the diagram, I also added a ribbon which is connected to the bottom stage of the rocket which also has its own shock cord.. This makes it easy to find and slows its descent. To get the highest apogee you'll need a D12-0 Estates engine for the bottom stage and D12-7 Estates engine on the upper stage.

Launch Lug

To make the fall-away launch lug you need a leftover piece of a body tube (preferably the same size as the rocket's body tube). It only need to be about 1-2 inches long. Make a cut down one side of the tube. On the other side you need to make a teeth pattern that is big enough to glue on a straw. There should be one tooth on one side and two on the other (see picture above). Use a cut up rubber band to connect the two pieces on the straight cut edge. Use any leftover rubber band to glue on the inside of both pieces. This will add more traction during launches. Next, take a straw and cut it to the same length of the cut up body tube. Cut that piece into a total of three pieces and glue them onto the teeth. Paint is not necessary but recommended for looks. You may also add your rocket's name on the launch lug as well. To set up the rocket you can wrap the launch lug around the rocket around the center of gravity. Then, line up the three straw pieces and slide them onto your launch rod. From here, you can set up everything else like normal. Once the rocket launches, the launch lug will fall off and it won't affect its flight in any way. If you don't want to go through this process, just simply glue on a couple pieces onto your model rocket (making sure they're lined up) and use it like that instead. Just as a disclaimer the fall away launch lug idea was not my idea. I found it in a model rocketry book and make a few small edits to it to improve it.

Engine setup

To get the highest apogee you'll need a D12-0 Estates engine for the bottom stage and D12-7 Estates engine on the upper stage. In order to get them to go off correctly, you'll need to add a small amount of scotch tape to hold them together, making sure that the D12-0 is on the bottom and both of the engines are facing the correct way. You will also have to wrap both of the engines with some masking tape to make sure the fit nice and snug into the rocket. Just be careful not to add too much tape as it can be hard to take out of the rocket afterwards. Before launch you also need to add the igniter and wadding just above the D12-7 engine. You may substitute the D12-7 engine with a D12-5 or a D12-3 engine but you'll lose some height during flight.

SkillsUSA Wisconsin State Championship

In 2016 I entered the model rocketry competition for SkillsUSA in Wisconsin. Through my model rocketry skills I was able to take third place in the competition. In 2017 I entered the contest a second time but unfortunately I made a miscalculation while assembling the model rocket and the rocket lost control and crashed into the ground. I did not place that year, but I did learn my lesson.

Third place medal for Model Rocketry competition in 2016.

If you have any ideas on how the design could be improved, questions on anything, or anything else please contact me. You can leave a comment or if you need a quick response send me an email at: [email protected]

title: Original Prusa i3 MK2 Print Bed Layout Guide

description.text:
UPDATE (3-26-17) - Layout was done incorrectly, should have had 5cm at top and bottom, not 10cm at top only, fixed STL to correct layout.

Occasionally I find it more difficult than I would like to avoid bad spots on my PEI (my fault for not prepping the surface correctly before printing with PETG). I can usually guess where my prints are going to land and avoid some bad spots, but I wanted a way to ensure I would know where I am printing.

This is a simple STL that you can load along with your desired print job and it helps visualize the areas to avoid. The STL is just the grid but you can easily pull this into Tinkercad to add visual references to any bad spots.

I am in the process of rebuilding my MK2 into an a new 3030 extrusion based enclosed frame so I don't want to replace my PEI sheet until everything gets moved over, so this is a good stop-gap until I replace it.

description.text:
Be prepared: This will take lots of supports and awkward cutting and sanding, unless you have a dual extruder and can use PVA for supports.
Needs very fine resolution.
6 sets of thumb screws + lids are printed, and 2 sets of mini ones + 2 more lids. The nut fits inside and the lid is glued onto it. They then act like wing nuts with any 6mm bolt passing through and are very effective at increasing the torture like so:

the shaft gets wound in and traps the balls in place by however much can be tolerated.
Then the balls get stretched down and clamped however tightly can be tolerated.
This clamp then gets screwed downward and stretches the sack by however much can be tolerated.
The bottom teeth then get wound up to meet the now very sensitive balls by however much can be tolerated.
The tip can then be put on a chain and padlock as well as a padlock through the part which holds the shaft in place.

Nuts and bolts needed are 6mm. The two side ones are 100mm long which I ordered special and they need hot gluing in place, otherwise they pop out of their seats next to the ring when the balls are stretched. You can find these here: http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/360742595943

Recommended at least 1mm wall and floor with infill above 40%. Wet and dry paper will also be needed to smooth everything. 180, 400, 800 grit going from rough to smooth. This will take the shine off so black gloss spray paint will bring it back,

Use either hot glue or solvent cement to join the parts. Hot glue is better at gap filling, while solvent cement is better for clean looks. Both are strong bonds.
Don't skimp on sanding thoroughly with wet and dry paper and removing all supports meticulously, as any slight sharp bit hurts in a way you don't want it to, trust me.

comments.text:
They are difficult prints. I believe during one I put extra support to sit on the skirt while it was printing to stop it coming off the bed, because the overhangs can warp and the extruder knocks into them.
Flame polishing sounds easier but this is more for acrylic, easy to ruin your PLA with this method. Sanding down is not fun, because there are so many nooks and crannies which are difficult to get the paper into it can take a long time, but you must remove all edges that you cut with the knife as believe me they do find there way into your sensitive areas when this is in use. I do think it's worth it though. I would do it all again if my one broke beyond repair.

description.text:
This is an emergency shutdown and smoke detector automatic shutdown system. When smoke is detected the printer will automatically have power cut off to it. The red button will do the same thing as well as for a trip test button.

Update: I realized the lid needed more screw holes so I added a new version. I also added just the tabs incase you already printed it and they can be glued on.

I used Kidde kn-cosm-ibca smoke and carbon monoxide alarm with battery backup. The relay is Kidde sm120x. If you can't find that manufacturer or model I am sure most other manufacturers make a similar relay module compatible with their alarm models.

This setup has been in use for several prints now and has worked well without any issues. It has been reassuring to know that it is there if something happens.

For my setup, I continue to use the normal on off switch that I had mounted on the power supply. It could easily be mounted to this unit also or you could put an on off switch instead of the trip test switch.

An open-source design of the N900s stylus for one of the best open-source phones out there ;-)
Compared to the original this model is slightly more edgy but this simplifies printing and gives a little more room for creating a nice finish.
I've included the Blender source so you can modify the pen as you like.
Update:
A word of warning: Since i had to take my measurements of a few pictures a friend of mine took of his original (because i lost mine long ago) i cannot guarantee sub-millimeter accuracy. Plastic parts are easy to modify after printing for making them fit but aluminum and alike are not, please keep that in mind.
One more thing... If you take the .stl and it's just about a cm in length and too narrow to print: Simply scale it up 10 times equally in every dimension. The length should be 9.9cm.

This particular part was printed on a BFB 3D-Touch at it's best resolution (0.125mm) but i think it should still work out at 0.25mm. The material used was PLA on a PLA raft (ABS is way too flexible). The small cylinder you can see in the rendering was necessary to slow down printing on the back part, without it the handle just melted while printing.
After printing you should start with removing leftovers from the raft with a file or similar and continue with sandpaper (in my case it was 120 grain) for a nice finish. Be carefull with the back part (the part sticking out of the case) so you don't sand it down too much and also leave the edges at the bottom side in tact. I did both things wrong so you don't have to ;-)

title: GoPro auto-panning rig using a cheap rotisserie motor
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I wanted a rig to pan my GoPro camera while my band is playing gigs, so came up with this set of things to do that using a cheap rotisserie motor. I wasn't sure about the motion geometry, so I just put a bunch of holes everywhere so I could try to discover a good combination that would be smooth and give me the range of motion I could live with. Some of the holes may be a little tight... I just drive the m3 bolts in and out until the plastic conforms to the threads. Kind of a cheater technique, I guess, but it seems to work ok. this is the motor I used:
http://www.amazon.com/GrillPro-60013-Replacement-Rotisserie-Motor/dp/B0000E2RH5/ref=sr_1_14?s=lawn-garden&ie=UTF8&qid=1335204205&sr=1-14 and here's a video of what the assembled thing does:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B3HdGH-5dP4 I have this shown sitting on a countertop, but the bracket has a hexnut location so this can be mounted on a tripod. Here's a short clip of what the panning motion looks like:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VvkOrj_IyqA&feature=youtu.be

You're going to need some m3 bolts of various lengths. This is kind of a starter set of parts. My parts work pretty good for me, but you might need to adjust them for your rotisserie motor. So I've included the openscad files if you want to adjust anything. I tried to comment things as best I could. Some things probably didn't get the documentation they deserve, but... such is life. Oh, you may need randyy's openscad library found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6021 Oh, and I'm using agwn's gopro extension arm found in the ancestry... http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10918

description.text:
This is a useful little thing for 750 g spools on Raise3D printers.
When using 750 g filament spools there's a problem with filament being trapped between the printer and the filament spool when the alternating push-draw makes the filament come off the spool. The filament is occasionally pushed back when the printerhead travels from far away from spool to close to the spool. There's then a risk that the filament jams and get stuck and eventually breaks when the extruder pulls. This happened for me as well, when I first got the printer and used other filaments than the large 1 kg spool from Raise3D.
Some solve this problem by adding a guide tube from the extruder to the printers top plate, but that's not necessary, - this little clip, that serves to keep the smaller spools very close to the printer, solves the problem perfectly. Never had issues with filament coming off the spool after starting to use this clip.

The clip prints without supports, as support is built-in. You have to break away the small taps in the slot.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a filament spool holder I created for the stock Monoprice Maker Select (i3) spool bracket. It utilizes a pair of 608 (skateboard) bearings for easier movement of the spool. I have had an eSun 1kg PLA spool on it for over 24 hours, no issues.

It is in early development, so USE AT YOUR OWN RISK!

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select (i3)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

50%

Notes:

I printed this with 50% infill for strength, because much of the spool weight is on the thinnest part of the plastic.

Printed in PLA

NEEDED:

2x M3 x 5mm screws
2x 608 Bearings (8mm ID, 22mm OD)

  1. Place the first bearing down the barrel of the larger spindle. Depending on the accuracy of your printer, you may need to apply force.
  2. Place the 2nd bearing on the smaller spindle, running it all the way down to the flange. Again, this may take some force, or some sandpaper to have a nicer finish on the small shaft.
  3. Mate the two pieces carefully. Be mindful of aligning the small spindle with the ID of the bearing inside of the larger spindle.
  4. I had to back the two pieces apart a bit so the bearings would spin freely.
  5. Put the large end of the smaller spindle into the bracket, and secure it by using the 2 x M3 screws.
  6. Place the filament spool onto the spindle and check that it is holding up. Spin it around, check for drooping etc. You wouldn't want the part failing in the middle of a long print.

Enjoy! Please comment and let me know of any improvements you'd like to see.

description.text:
I required a better way to mount new extruder design to the solidoodle gantry while being ridged and easily maintained.

This design very well solved this problem and can be seen working in the video mentioned in the pictures and or the link below.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7fMubUq-1mw

First, print out the upgrade and make sure it don't have any layer problems or layer adhesion problems and it is pretty well dimensional sound. Also, make sure you make a mount so you can incorporate a new extruder into the design.

Then, All you need to do is remove the four 3mm screws holding the gantry. Two get removed from the top of the the old extruder mount. Remove those first. Then, remove the one screw at the base were the nylon square piece is and remove one or two of those screws to remove the gantry piece to be replaced.

Install and if you would like, use loctite and glue the six 3mm nuts into the mid gantry piece. Then resemble the gantry piece onto the mid gantry assembly. Then, put your extruder back on and you should be good to go!

This upgrade has completely resolved my random layer issues on my solidoodle printers. The print head no longer can be moved when I tray to move it with my hand. You will see a large quality increase but please make sure you test your extruder mount to this upgrade piece before disassemble your printer. As always, I am not responsible for any damage or liability to your upgrade.

Please enjoy! I am and I am happy to share all of my successes on thingiverse! Please leave a comment either here on thingiverse or on the video on YouTube. Thank you! Have a great day!
